The exact founding date of the shrine is unknown. However, records indicate that during the {{ill|Genroku era|ja|元禄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genroku era|qq=}} (1688–1704), a shrine called '''"Suibō Inari" (Water Protection Inari, 水防稲荷)''' was enshrined within its grounds. This suggests that '''Ontake Shrine was already in existence during the early Edo period'''<ref name="shrine">埼玉県神社庁神社調査団 編『埼玉の神社 大里・北葛飾・比企』埼玉県神社庁、1992nd year 、562-563p</ref>.

The '''shrine was originally associated with the Buddhist temple''' '''"Tōfuku-ji" (東福寺),''' which acted as its '''bettō-ji (別当寺, shrine-adjacent temple).''' However, with the '''Meiji period's policy of separating Buddhism and Shinto (神仏分離, Shinbutsu Bunri), Tōfuku-ji was abolished''' in the early Meiji period<ref name="shrine"></ref>.

